<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="aarrr-pirate-metrics">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>growth-marketer</domain>
    <summary>Five-stage framework (Acquisition, Activation, Retention, Revenue, Referral) tracking one metric per stage to identify growth bottlenecks and fix the weakest lever first.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>growth-metrics</tag>
      <tag>funnel-analysis</tag>
      <tag>pirate-metrics</tag>
      <tag>acquisition</tag>
      <tag>retention</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>metrics</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>AARRR Pirate Metrics</title>
    <summary>A five-stage growth measurement framework — Acquisition, Activation, Retention, Revenue, Referral — that provides a complete picture of the user journey. Each stage has one key metric, a benchmark range, and a diagnostic question. The framework forces prioritization: identify the weakest stage and fix it before scaling the others.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Tracking too many metrics leads to tracking nothing. AARRR assigns ownership of each growth lever to a distinct measurement, surfaces the actual bottleneck in the funnel, and prevents the common failure of scaling acquisition before fixing a broken activation or retention stage.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Setting up a growth measurement system for a new product or team.</item>
        <item>Weekly/monthly business reviews where a single dashboard must cover the full funnel.</item>
        <item>Diagnosing why revenue growth has stalled despite healthy acquisition.</item>
        <item>Onboarding a new growth hire or co-founder to shared growth vocabulary.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-launch with zero users — benchmarks and funnels require real cohort data to be meaningful.</item>
        <item>Products with complex multi-sided markets where a single AARRR stack misrepresents both sides.</item>
        <item>When you need deep cohort or segmentation analysis — AARRR is a summary frame, not a substitute for cohort tools.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Framework Rule">
      <rule>
        <statement>Track exactly one key metric per AARRR stage; identify the weakest stage and fix it before increasing investment in any other stage.</statement>
        <rationale>Scaling acquisition into a broken activation or retention stage multiplies waste proportionally. The weakest stage is always the highest-ROI fix because every downstream stage is bottlenecked by it.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Acquisition">
      <p>Question: How do users find you? Key metric: CPA (marketing spend / new users). Benchmark: below $50 for SaaS. Secondary: sign-up rate (sign-ups / visitors), target 2-5%. Track channel mix to maintain diverse, resilient acquisition.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Activation">
      <p>Question: Do users experience core value? Key metric: activation rate (activated users / sign-ups). Benchmark: 30-50% good, 50%+ great. Time to first value (TTV) target: under 10 minutes. Onboarding completion target: 60-80%.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Define activation as the specific action that correlates with D30 retention — never as a setup milestone like "created profile" that does not predict long-term usage.</statement>
        <rationale>Wrong activation metrics optimize for vanity actions. The correlation test is empirical: run regression between candidate actions and D30 retention; the action with the highest correlation is the correct activation event.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Retention">
      <p>Question: Do users come back? Key metrics: D1 (target 40-60%), D7 (target 20-30%), D30 (target 10-15%) retention. Churn rate target: below 5%/month for SaaS. Formula: Dx retention = active on day X / signups from that cohort.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Revenue">
      <p>Question: How do you monetize? Key metrics: MRR (paying customers × avg monthly price), ARPU (total revenue / users), LTV (ARPU × avg customer lifespan in months), free-to-paid rate for freemium. LTV target: greater than 3× CAC.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Referral">
      <p>Question: Do users tell others? Key metrics: K-factor (invites sent × invite conversion rate; above 1.0 = viral), referral rate (referred users / total users, benchmark 5-15%), NPS (% promoters minus % detractors, target above 50).</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Weekly Dashboard Structure">
      <p>The weekly AARRR dashboard has five sections, one per stage. Acquisition: visitors, sign-ups, CPA by channel, week-over-week delta. Activation: rate, TTV. Retention: cohort table with D1/D7/D30 for recent cohorts. Revenue: MRR, new MRR, churned MRR, ARPU. Referral: invites, conversions, K-factor.</p>
      <reference path="templates/weekly-dashboard.md">Weekly AARRR report template</reference>
    </section>
    <section name="SaaS Example">
      <example type="good">
        <note>Project management tool. Acquisition: 2,000 monthly sign-ups. Activation: 35% completed first project (target 50% — this is the priority fix before scaling acquisition). Retention: D30 at 18%. Revenue: 3% free-to-paid conversion. Referral: K-factor 0.05. Priority: activation is the bottleneck; fixing it from 35% to 50% would increase downstream revenue by 43% with zero additional acquisition spend.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="E-commerce Example">
      <example type="good">
        <note>Acquisition: 50,000 monthly visitors. Activation: 12% add-to-cart. Retention: 8% repeat purchase within 30 days. Revenue: 2.5% overall conversion rate. Referral: 1% share rate. Priority: retention (8% repeat purchase) — email re-engagement sequence and loyalty program are highest ROI next moves.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Mobile App Example">
      <example type="good">
        <note>Acquisition: 5,000 downloads/month at $2.50 CAC. Activation: 40% created first workout. Retention: D1 55%, D7 30%, D30 15%. Revenue: 4% free-to-premium conversion, $8/month ARPU, $48 LTV. Referral: 5% invite rate, 15% referral conversion, K-factor 0.075. LTV:CAC ratio 19:1 — healthy economics, main lever is improving D7 retention to D30.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Implementation Steps">
      <list>
        <item>Define one key metric per stage before building any dashboard.</item>
        <item>Set up tracking in GA4, Mixpanel, or Amplitude with one event per funnel step.</item>
        <item>Validate activation event by correlating candidate actions with D30 retention in cohort data.</item>
        <item>Create weekly dashboard with targets per stage and week-over-week deltas.</item>
        <item>Review weekly; identify worst-performing stage; run one experiment to improve it.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Tracking more than one metric per AARRR stage.</description>
        <reason>Multiple metrics per stage create analysis paralysis and diffuse ownership. Each stage needs one accountable number; secondary metrics are context, not targets.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Focusing investment on acquisition when activation or retention is broken.</description>
        <reason>Every new user acquired into a broken funnel is waste multiplied. Fix the weakest stage first; the downstream revenue impact is proportional to acquisition volume.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Defining activation as "created profile" or another setup action that does not predict retention.</description>
        <reason>Optimizing for setup completion inflates activation rate while the product's retention remains flat. The only valid activation definition is an action empirically correlated with D30 retention.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Not segmenting AARRR metrics by acquisition channel or cohort.</description>
        <reason>Aggregate metrics mask variation. A strong paid-search cohort can hide poor organic retention; blending them produces a misleading average that leads to wrong investment decisions.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Ignoring the referral stage until late in product maturity.</description>
        <reason>Referral programs take 3-6 months to generate meaningful signal. Starting instrumentation and basic mechanics early means the data is available when it is needed for scaling decisions.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/weekly-dashboard.md" purpose="Weekly AARRR report template with per-stage metric tables"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
